00:19:34,955 --> 00:19:38,049
Mother. Mother, I thought we
were going to be able to talk.

240
00:19:38,160 --> 00:19:40,219
-We will. We will.
<i>-Ida, Sam.</i>

241
00:19:40,327 --> 00:19:42,375
<i>Oh, God. She's got
what's her name with her.</i>

242
00:19:42,401 --> 00:19:43,083
<i>Yoo-hoo!</i>

243
00:19:43,164 --> 00:19:45,394
Sam!

244
00:19:45,500 --> 00:19:50,300
Well, Alma. How are you?
You look wonderful.

245
00:19:50,404 --> 00:19:53,169
Hello, Shirley.

246
00:19:53,275 --> 00:19:55,766
Thank you, Spiro.

247
00:19:55,876 --> 00:19:57,970
-Salt?
-Not yet.

248
00:19:58,078 --> 00:20:00,444
Sam, happy Christmas.

249
00:20:02,550 --> 00:20:04,576
<i>-So sorry we're late.</i>
-Thanks.

250
00:20:04,685 --> 00:20:07,119
<i>Now, Alma...</i>

251
00:20:07,221 --> 00:20:09,190
what are you going to have?

252
00:20:09,290 --> 00:20:13,057
I can't make up my mind whether to
have the number one or the number two.

253
00:20:13,161 --> 00:20:16,493
-What do you recommend, Spiro?
-Between you and me, madame...

254
00:20:16,597 --> 00:20:18,498
today the number two.

255
00:20:18,599 --> 00:20:22,000
Thank you, Spiro. Shirley. Shirley,
what are you going to have?

256
00:20:22,103 --> 00:20:26,335
Between you and me, mademoiselle,
today the number one.

257
00:20:26,441 --> 00:20:30,308
-Madame Lowry?
-Oh, to hell with the diet.

258
00:20:30,412 --> 00:20:32,573
I'm going to have a
number eight, please.

259
00:20:32,681 --> 00:20:35,275
A most perceptive choice
if I dare say so, madame.

260
00:20:35,299 --> 00:20:36,163
Oh, Ida!

261
00:20:36,250 --> 00:20:38,151
-Monsieur.
-Steak, please. Rare. Mother...

262
00:20:38,252 --> 00:20:39,247
-Monsieur, quel numero?

263
00:20:39,271 --> 00:20:41,302
-I don't know which number.
Mother, please...

264
00:20:41,388 --> 00:20:43,755
-That one. There.
-That's fine. Thanks.

265
00:20:43,858 --> 00:20:46,588
-Mother, will you please listen to me.
-Alma! You wicked girl.

266
00:20:46,694 --> 00:20:49,788
-You've started your treatment.
-Say the number, please.

267
00:20:49,897 --> 00:20:53,197
-You noticed.
-You have to say the number!

268
00:20:53,300 --> 00:20:54,944
Will you please go away!
I'm trying to talk...

269
00:20:54,970 --> 00:20:56,088
I must tell you all about it.

270
00:20:56,171 --> 00:20:58,138
Number three.

271
00:20:59,374 --> 00:21:01,342
Mother, will you listen to me.
I haven't...

272
00:21:01,442 --> 00:21:03,569
<i>Numero huit.</i>

273
00:21:04,679 --> 00:21:08,944
Braised veal in wine sauce.

274
00:21:11,051 --> 00:21:16,148
It's too exciting. I've left
Dr. Jaffe and gone to Dr. Chapman.

275
00:21:16,258 --> 00:21:18,885
-Numero deux. Duck a l'orange.
-Dr. Chapman? Chapman?

276
00:21:18,993 --> 00:21:20,894
Excusez-moi.

277
00:21:20,996 --> 00:21:23,395
The acid man?

278
00:21:23,498 --> 00:21:26,898
Really, Ida! Just because his
techniques are revolutionary...

279
00:21:27,001 --> 00:21:30,232
I don't go around calling
Dr. Jaffe the knife man.

280
00:21:30,337 --> 00:21:32,897
<i>Numero un, crevettes
a la mayonnaise.</i>

281
00:21:33,008 --> 00:21:35,179
I am sorry, Alma. I didn't
mean to sound so...

282
00:21:35,203 --> 00:21:36,865
It's all right, Ida.
It's just...

283
00:21:36,944 --> 00:21:40,881
<i>Steak. Numéro trois.</i>

284
00:21:41,916 --> 00:21:45,215
<i>Mesdames, monsieur...</i>

285
00:21:45,319 --> 00:21:47,345
<i>Bon appetit!</i>

286
00:21:47,454 --> 00:21:49,650
<i>-Merci.
-Merci.</i>

287
00:21:49,758 --> 00:21:54,092
Acid, on the other hand, can be used
for such wonderfully subtle shading.

288
00:21:54,194 --> 00:21:56,185
Such delicate nuances.

289
00:21:56,298 --> 00:21:58,528
Like a Rembrandt etching.

290
00:21:58,633 --> 00:22:01,067
-And it is so much quicker.
-God!

291
00:22:01,169 --> 00:22:03,030
If it wasn't for this complication...
the doctor

292
00:22:03,056 --> 00:22:04,651
says it could have
happened to anybody...

293
00:22:04,739 --> 00:22:06,638
I'd have had this
dressing off yesterday.

294
00:22:06,740 --> 00:22:09,073
Shirley.

295
00:22:10,278 --> 00:22:13,008
Salt?

296
00:22:34,669 --> 00:22:36,568
What were we saying?

297
00:22:36,671 --> 00:22:39,970
-This isn't rare.
-Oh! By the by, Alma...

298
00:22:40,075 --> 00:22:43,806
I saw the most wonderful idea for
Christmas presents at the chemist's.

299
00:22:43,912 --> 00:22:46,744
Gift tokens. Medical
gift tokens.

300
00:22:46,847 --> 00:22:48,748
Oh, that sounds marvelous!

301
00:22:48,849 --> 00:22:52,286
It's good at any doctor's and
most of the major hospitals.

302
00:22:52,386 --> 00:22:55,913
It's also accepted for
gynecological examinations...

303
00:22:56,023 --> 00:22:58,423
<i>including cesarean section.</i>

304
00:22:58,526 --> 00:22:59,209
Spiro.

305
00:22:59,233 --> 00:23:01,280
I'm sorry, madame.
I don't know what to say.

306
00:23:01,363 --> 00:23:03,330
It never really happens to us.

307
00:23:03,431 --> 00:23:05,625
I'm going to do something
about it straightaway.

308
00:23:05,733 --> 00:23:09,431
Really, Sam! Why can't you do
something about these terrorists?

309
00:23:09,537 --> 00:23:12,563
It's my lunch hour.

310
00:23:12,673 --> 00:23:14,732
Besides, it's not my department.

311
00:23:14,843 --> 00:23:19,404
Actually, Alma, that was one of the little
things I've been dying to tell you.

312
00:23:19,513 --> 00:23:24,644
Look. Sam's been promoted
to Information Retrieval.

313
00:23:24,752 --> 00:23:28,654
Oh, that's wonderful!
Congratulations, Sam!

314
00:23:28,757 --> 00:23:32,488
Stop it! I'm not being promoted. I'm
not going to Information Retrieval.

315
00:23:32,594 --> 00:23:36,222
If I want you to stick your oar in,
Mother, I'll tell you where to stick it.

316
00:23:40,268 --> 00:23:42,236
Pepper?

317
00:23:43,872 --> 00:23:45,771
I've gotta go.

318
00:23:45,874 --> 00:23:48,672
-Sam, you haven't had your dessert.
-I don't want dessert.

319
00:23:48,777 --> 00:23:50,799
I don't want promotion.
I don't want anything.

320
00:23:50,825 --> 00:23:52,201
Of course you want something.

321
00:23:52,279 --> 00:23:55,113
You must have hopes,
wishes, dreams!

322
00:23:55,215 --> 00:23:57,582
No, nothing. Not even dreams.

323
00:24:08,128 --> 00:24:10,256
Sam.

324
00:24:42,262 --> 00:24:43,230
Sam!

325
00:25:23,304 --> 00:25:26,467
Oh, God.

326
00:25:49,297 --> 00:25:51,628
Hello. Central Services?

327
00:25:51,732 --> 00:25:54,792
I'm at 579B, Block 19,
Northwestern Section "D."

328
00:25:54,903 --> 00:25:58,134
That's exit one on Green Pastures
Highway at the Orange Blossom Flyover.

329
00:25:58,239 --> 00:26:01,730
And I've got trouble with my
air-conditioning. It's an emergency.

330
00:26:01,843 --> 00:26:03,742
Thank you for calling
Central Services.

331
00:26:03,845 --> 00:26:05,744
I'm sorry. Due to temporary
staff shortage...

332
00:26:05,846 --> 00:26:10,546
Central Services cannot take service calls
centrally between 2300 and 0900 hours.

333
00:26:10,652 --> 00:26:13,048
Have a nice day. This has
not been a recording.

334
00:26:13,074 --> 00:26:14,270
This is an emergency.

335
00:26:14,355 --> 00:26:16,653
Thank you for calling Central Services.
I'm sorry. Due to...

336
00:26:16,758 --> 00:26:19,989
-No. I've got to have a heating engineer.
-Thank you for calling Central Services.

337
00:26:20,094 --> 00:26:21,993
Oh, shit.

338
00:26:46,621 --> 00:26:48,520
Hello.

339
00:26:57,832 --> 00:26:59,959
-Hello.
-Hello.

340
00:27:01,001 --> 00:27:03,402
-Hello.
-Hello.

341
00:27:05,506 --> 00:27:07,598
-Hello.
-Hello.

342
00:27:09,042 --> 00:27:10,942
Hello. Mr. Lowry.

343
00:27:11,045 --> 00:27:13,012
Yes. Who is this?

344
00:27:13,114 --> 00:27:16,549
Put the phone down and
raise your hands.

345
00:27:16,651 --> 00:27:18,618
What? Who is this?

346
00:27:22,123 --> 00:27:24,090
Nice and easy now.

347
00:27:24,192 --> 00:27:26,160
Nice and easy.

348
00:27:30,265 --> 00:27:32,893
Just keep your hands
where I can see them.

349
00:27:56,990 --> 00:27:59,356
What... What are you doing?

350
00:28:04,565 --> 00:28:06,795
Harry Tuttle. Heating
engineer at your service.

351
00:28:11,471 --> 00:28:13,997
Tuttle?

352
00:28:14,107 --> 00:28:16,008
Are you from Central Services?

353
00:28:21,950 --> 00:28:23,884
I called Central Services.

354
00:28:23,984 --> 00:28:26,419
Well, they're a little
overworked these days.

355
00:28:26,520 --> 00:28:28,682
Luckily I intercepted your call.

356
00:28:28,789 --> 00:28:31,554
You did...

357
00:28:32,660 --> 00:28:35,924
<i>Just a minute. What was
that business with the gun?</i>

358
00:28:36,029 --> 00:28:37,963
It's just a precaution, sir.

359
00:28:38,066 --> 00:28:39,965
Just a precaution.

360
00:28:40,067 --> 00:28:43,002
I've had traps set
for me before now.

361
00:28:43,104 --> 00:28:45,595
And there are plenty of
people in Central Services...

362
00:28:45,707 --> 00:28:47,867
who'd love to get their
hands on Harry Tuttle.

363
00:28:50,111 --> 00:28:52,306
Are you telling me
that this is illegal?

364
00:28:58,885 --> 00:29:00,904
Well, yes and no. Officially,
only Central Service

365
00:29:00,930 --> 00:29:02,710
operatives are supposed
to touch this stuff.

366
00:29:02,789 --> 00:29:04,690
-Would you hold this, please?
-Uh...

367
00:29:04,791 --> 00:29:07,089
But nowadays, with all the
new rules and regulations...

368
00:29:07,194 --> 00:29:09,163
they can't get decent
staff anymore.

369
00:29:09,262 --> 00:29:12,163
So they tend to turn a blind
eye as long as I'm careful.

370
00:29:12,266 --> 00:29:15,565
Mind you, if ever they could prove that
I've been working on their equipment...

371
00:29:15,670 --> 00:29:17,900
well, that's a pipe
of a different color.

372
00:29:18,006 --> 00:29:20,804
-Wouldn't it be simpler just to work...
-Would you hold this for me?

373
00:29:20,907 --> 00:29:24,344
Sorry. Yes. I was saying, wouldn't it be
simpler to work with Central Services?

374
00:29:24,444 --> 00:29:26,935
Nah! Nah. Couldn't
stand the pa...

375
00:29:27,048 --> 00:29:29,778
We're getting warm.

376
00:29:29,884 --> 00:29:31,586
You couldn't what?
Couldn't stand the what?

377
00:29:31,612 --> 00:29:33,275
Paperwork. Couldn't
stand the paperwork.

378
00:29:33,354 --> 00:29:36,721
Listen. This whole system of
yours could be on fire...

379
00:29:36,824 --> 00:29:40,988
and I couldn't even turn on a kitchen
tap without filling out a 27 B/6.

380
00:29:41,095 --> 00:29:43,790
Bloody paperwork.

381
00:29:43,897 --> 00:29:46,093
I suppose one has to
expect a certain amount.

382
00:29:46,200 --> 00:29:49,169
Why? I came into this game for
the action, the excitement.

383
00:29:49,269 --> 00:29:54,401
Go anywhere, travel light, get in, get out,
wherever there's trouble, a man alone.

384
00:29:54,509 --> 00:29:58,444
Now they got the whole country sectioned
off. You can't make a move without a form.

385
00:30:14,127 --> 00:30:16,061
Found it.

386
00:30:16,163 --> 00:30:18,064
There's your problem.

387
00:30:18,165 --> 00:30:20,099
-Can you fix it?
-No, I can't.

388
00:30:20,201 --> 00:30:23,897
But I can bypass it
with one of these.

389
00:30:26,173 --> 00:30:28,142
Fine by me.

390
00:30:32,380 --> 00:30:34,347
-Are you expecting anyone?
-No.

391
00:30:39,019 --> 00:30:42,250
-Get down!
-Wait! Wait! Will you wait!

392
00:30:43,290 --> 00:30:45,259
Shh.

393
00:30:48,429 --> 00:30:51,557
The flashlight.

394
00:30:53,534 --> 00:30:55,433
Central Services.

395
00:30:55,536 --> 00:30:57,435
-Central Services.
-Oh, yes.

396
00:30:57,538 --> 00:30:59,438
-You rang, sir?
-You rang, sir?

397
00:30:59,539 --> 00:31:01,837
-Trouble with your air-conditioning?
-Air-conditioning, sir?

398
00:31:01,942 --> 00:31:04,275
No, it's... it's...
it's, uh, all right.

399
00:31:04,377 --> 00:31:07,438
It's, um... It's fixed.

400
00:31:07,548 --> 00:31:09,242
-Fixed.
-Fixed?

401
00:31:09,349 --> 00:31:11,250
Yes, um...

402
00:31:11,352 --> 00:31:13,547
I mean, it, um, fixed itself.

403
00:31:13,653 --> 00:31:16,213
-Oh, it fixed itself!
-Fixed itself?

404
00:31:16,324 --> 00:31:18,519
Yes!

405
00:31:18,625 --> 00:31:20,526
Machines don't fix themselves.

406
00:31:20,627 --> 00:31:22,823
No, they don't fix
themselves, sir.

407
00:31:22,930 --> 00:31:26,330
-He's tampered with it, Dowser.
-I think he's tampered with it, Mr. Spoor.

408
00:31:26,433 --> 00:31:28,334
Sorry you've had a
wasted journey.

409
00:31:28,435 --> 00:31:30,336
Oh, that's all right.

410
00:31:30,438 --> 00:31:32,905
-I think we'll go have a little look.
-No, you can't.

411
00:31:33,007 --> 00:31:35,270
I think we should.
Yes, Mr. Spoor.

412
00:31:35,375 --> 00:31:37,708
Have you got a 27 B/6?

413
00:31:37,811 --> 00:31:40,302
27 B/6?

414
00:31:40,413 --> 00:31:42,314
27 B/6?

415
00:31:42,415 --> 00:31:44,748
<i>27...</i>

416
00:31:46,753 --> 00:31:48,653
Now look what
you've done to him!

417
00:31:48,756 --> 00:31:52,782
Well, have you got a 27 B/6?

418
00:31:52,894 --> 00:31:55,657
Not... as such.

419
00:31:57,030 --> 00:31:58,931
But we'll get one.

420
00:31:59,032 --> 00:32:01,278
It's all right. It's all right.
It's all right.

421
00:32:01,303 --> 00:32:02,423
It's all right, then?

422
00:32:02,502 --> 00:32:05,836
Sorry. I'm a bit of a stickler
for paperwork, you see.

423
00:32:05,940 --> 00:32:09,000
I mean, where would we be if we didn't
stick to the correct procedures?

424
00:32:09,109 --> 00:32:11,509
We'll be back.

425
00:32:11,612 --> 00:32:13,671
We'll be back!

426
00:32:15,516 --> 00:32:18,279
It's all right.

427
00:32:18,385 --> 00:32:20,286
Thanks for coming.

428
00:32:20,387 --> 00:32:22,288
We'll be back, you
clever little bastard!

429
00:32:22,390 --> 00:32:24,914
<i>-Thank you.
-We'll show you!</i>

430
00:32:31,596 --> 00:32:32,424
Well...

431
00:32:32,432 --> 00:32:35,433
Thanks, Lowry. You're a
good man in a tight corner.

432
00:32:35,435 --> 00:32:37,461
Thanks.

433
00:32:40,208 --> 00:32:42,732
Listen, um... I, uh...

434
00:32:43,810 --> 00:32:45,438
Well, I...

435
00:32:45,546 --> 00:32:47,844
I just happen to work at the
Ministry of Information.

436
00:32:47,949 --> 00:32:50,440
-What?
-And, uh...

437
00:32:50,550 --> 00:32:55,113
Well, I just happen to know
that Information Retrieval...

438
00:32:55,222 --> 00:32:58,852
are looking for an Archibald
Tuttle, heating engineer.

439
00:32:59,894 --> 00:33:01,794
You, uh...

440
00:33:01,895 --> 00:33:04,193
You wouldn't, by any chance...

441
00:33:04,298 --> 00:33:05,992
Would you?

442
00:33:07,234 --> 00:33:09,999
My good friends call me Harry.

443
00:33:11,305 --> 00:33:13,967
Information Retrieval, huh?

444
00:33:14,075 --> 00:33:16,406
The big boys.

445
00:33:21,182 --> 00:33:23,082
What do they want you for?

446
00:33:27,622 --> 00:33:30,089
-Time to go.
-Sorry.

447
00:33:30,191 --> 00:33:32,659
How's that?

448
00:33:35,695 --> 00:33:38,664
Listen, you, um... you really
must let me give you something.

449
00:33:44,271 --> 00:33:47,605
How much will it be for the, uh...
for the work?

450
00:33:47,708 --> 00:33:49,607
Ah, come on.

451
00:33:49,710 --> 00:33:52,679
You did me a favor. Just
check the corridor.

452
00:33:54,015 --> 00:33:56,915
Oh. Well, thanks.

453
00:33:57,018 --> 00:33:59,919
Listen, kid, we're
all in it together.

454
00:34:00,020 --> 00:34:02,318
-Go on.
-Right.

455
00:34:07,827 --> 00:34:10,626
Okay.

456
00:34:15,302 --> 00:34:17,271
All clear.

457
00:34:45,365 --> 00:34:47,960
I think Kurtzmann is
getting suspicious.

458
00:34:50,670 --> 00:34:53,400
What's playing today?

459
00:34:53,507 --> 00:34:55,407
<i>Casablanca.</i>

460
00:34:55,509 --> 00:34:58,478
<i>Mr. Lowry, will you
step in here, please.</i>

461
00:35:01,548 --> 00:35:03,516
<i>Lowry!</i>

462
00:35:05,085 --> 00:35:07,577
<i>Sam Lowry!</i>

463
00:35:14,728 --> 00:35:16,697
Psst!

464
00:35:19,099 --> 00:35:22,228
Thank God you're here.
We're in terrible trouble.

465
00:35:22,335 --> 00:35:23,963
Shh.

466
00:35:30,710 --> 00:35:33,440
-Look at this. Look at this.
-It's a check.

467
00:35:33,547 --> 00:35:35,447
It's the refund for Tuttle.

468
00:35:35,548 --> 00:35:37,449
-Tuttle?
-Mm-hmm.

469
00:35:37,550 --> 00:35:40,452
No, no. Buttle. I mean Buttle.

470
00:35:40,554 --> 00:35:42,748
It's been confusion
from the word go.

471
00:35:42,856 --> 00:35:45,757
He's been overcharged for
Information Retrieval procedures...

472
00:35:45,860 --> 00:35:48,760
and someone somewhere is trying
to make us carry the can.

473
00:35:48,862 --> 00:35:52,298
Can I have a look? I've never
seen a refund check before.

474
00:35:52,400 --> 00:35:54,367
I'll bet it's Jeffries.

475
00:35:56,469 --> 00:35:58,369
Yes.

476
00:35:58,472 --> 00:36:01,373
He always believes that people should
pay more for their interrogation.

477
00:36:01,474 --> 00:36:03,375
And "B," he loathes me.

478
00:36:03,476 --> 00:36:05,376
We've gotta get rid of it!

479
00:36:05,478 --> 00:36:07,378
Well, send it to somebody else.

480
00:36:07,481 --> 00:36:10,382
Better still, send it to Buttle.
After all, it's his check.

481
00:36:10,483 --> 00:36:12,884
I've tried that. But look.
Look at this.

482
00:36:12,987 --> 00:36:16,945
You see? The population census has
gotten him down as "dormanted."

483
00:36:17,056 --> 00:36:20,458
Uh, the Central Collective Storehouse
